Enzo, who was known for being a bit of a fool, immediately made a fool of himself by tripping on the way into the coffee shop and nearly knocking over a table. Paulin, on the other hand, was the complete opposite of Enzo - good looking and smooth, he seemed to have everything going for him.

As they sat down at a table, the tension between the four of them was palpable. Leon and Amine didn't seem to know what to say, and Enzo kept making inappropriate jokes that no one found funny. Paulin, meanwhile, seemed to be in his own world, staring off into space and ignoring the others.

Despite the awkwardness, the four of them managed to make small talk and finish their drinks. As they said their goodbyes and went their separate ways, it was clear that this meetup had been a disaster. It was unlikely that they would be seeing each other again anytime soon.

Invitées en maison de repos pour explorer leurs troubles sexuels, trois jeunes femmes occupent les jours et les nuits à apprivoiser leurs démons intimes. Sous la supervision tranquille d’une thérapeute allemande et d’un travailleur social bienveillant, le groupe tente de garder un équilibre fragile.

Dans une Argentine divisée entre un conservatisme profond et un élan féministe inédit, le film dépeint les trajets de Claudia et Violeta, dans leur cheminement politique et leur vie intime. Femmes trans se revendiquant travesties, elles se heurtent avec leurs camarades à la violence patriarcale, jusque dans leur chair. Convaincues d’être les actrices d’une révolution en cours à la croisée des luttes, face à la défiance du vieux monde elles redoublent d’énergie pour inventer le présent, aimer et rester en vie.

Anaïs, jeune et talentueuse actrice de théâtre, est si investie dans son nouveau rôle de Sarah Kane dans Psychose 4:48 que sa relation avec son mentor et réalisateur devient impossible. Après une énième dispute, elle décide de tout quitter et part pour Londres marcher dans les pas de son héroïne. De retour en France, complètement bouleversée par cette expérience, elle décide de faire table rase du passé en se séparant de son amant et en tombant amoureuse d’une femme…

Élisabeth de Raincy, Présidente de la République, a choisi de se retirer de la vie politique. À trois jours du premier tour de l’élection présidentielle, elle apprend par son secrétaire général, Franck L’Herbier, qu’un scandale venant de l’étranger va éclabousser son successeur désigné et donner la victoire au candidat d’extrême-droite. Ils ont trois jours pour changer le cours de l’histoire. Par tous les moyens...

Attitudes towards LGBT family visiting from US

I was born in the Philippines but have lived most of my life as an out of the closet gay male here in the United States. I currently have a boyfriend. My mom and dad both know I'm gay who both live here in the US however many of my family still residing in the Philippines don't know this.

I live a normal life here in the US, all my coworkers, friends, roommates, landlords all know I'm gay. I've never needed to hide it. I'm not a really a feminine or flamboyant type of gay either. Many people in the states I meet for the first time are often surprised to learn that I am gay saying they wouldn't have ever guessed.

>>175345968
>what if something expensive breaks and you must replace it?

That's what the "salary exceeds inflation rate" part is supposed to solve. If it's very expensive, you can take a loan or just buy foreign currencies.

>What if you're trying to save for a house

First of all, housing market is usually adjusted to local customers' purchasing power, usually in case of high inflation for consumer goods, housing prices RELATIVELY go down (doesn't always mean nominally, the point is that the pace of growth of housing prices is considerably slower than inflation rate for other types of goods).

That's why:

>Soaring inflation makes the numbers a little more complicated to interpret, however, and the real figure for house-price growth was 30% in the year to March, when consumer price inflation sat at 69.9%, according to Knight Frank’s data.

Hence in case of high consumer price inflation, houses are actually relatively cheaper to buy, especially if salary keeps growing above the CPI-adjusted inflation rate.

Secondly, again there is "economy adjusted to culture" thing. Not in every country housing market is actually a market itself. In many cases in those so called "not first world countries" houses are self-built, for many years, with help of the family, on your own plot of land, so their price is largely not tied to the capital market. Not to mention "increased consumption" the government wants to encourage you to with a high inflation rate can as well pertain to building materials which are a means of saving money (while being essentially a consumer good) itself.

Most important thing - never try to understand the economy outside your Germanic bubble with a mind limited to Germanic way of life and doing things

>>175270421
paleolithic oogaboogaspeak
turns out Hopi has a segmentative aspect which is like iterative but also changes the precise meaning of the verb, so "to be notched" becomes "to be serrated", and I'm thinking of including these types of aspects in my verb system too, which I've already made to be reliant on both norm-dependent context and inanimate/animate division of nouns in order to preserve free word order
tldr you can say lion killed deer, deer killed lion, deer lion killed, but they all mean "lion killed deer". To say "deer killed lion", you slap the second ergative on deer and a reverse-norm absolutive marker on the verb and there we go
this would be a lot simpler if the ergative I and absolutive case endings weren't 0, but I that's just not how I roll

>>175272225
I've mostly kept to romanizations since I'm not too great with visual arts otherwise. With the current one I'm making, I've been in a trend of using <h> for a lot, especially aspiration & voicelessness, and really put an emphasis on connective speech to make changes. <j> is also fun too since it creates opportunities for palatalization, and I think it can make for some good sound changes by adding it to a consonant or a cluster. So for instance,

>I read the book.
>I'agent DEF book patient read.PRES.1sg
Poh'an therah degam ett de.
Literary: /ˈpoʔɑn ˈtʰɛrɑ ˈdɛɡɑm ɛt de/
Connective: ['poʔɑ̃ˈtʰɛrɑˈdɛɡʌ̃ˈɛtːe]

Degam can also be realized as [dɛɡʌ̃m]. I eventually will tend to make it more complex, toying with word-initial devoicing, making "degam" more like "hdegam", /tɛɡɑm/, etc. (hdhegam for /tʰ.../ lmao) I also really like the idea of splitting up noun case markers much more literally, and I think I get a bit more mileage out if it than just doing nom/acc or erg/abs, because it's not insanely constrained one way or the other. I haven't done much with verbs yet, but I plan on creating connective sentences by adding postfixes or other postpositions a la Japanese. A bit more of a showcase, but I'm pretty happy that it's a good foundation and visually appealing without being overbearing.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>175297945
It depends if it's an action you're doing to yourself or a status/adjective.
When you build a sentence in french, think of "who?" is being affected by the action. Here's a few examples with word by word translation.

>Je me rase.
I shave (who?) myself.
>Je me suis approché de lui.
I have approached (who?) myself to him.
>Je m'entraine en français.
I train (who?) myself in french.

But if it's a status.
>Je suis arrivé.
I am arrived.
>Je suis tombé.
I am fallen.
In this case, "arrived" or "fallen" is not a action you're doing to yourself. It's a status, you are currently in a particular situation.

>why not j'ai approché ?
It's correct if you talk about something else than you. Example:
>J'ai approché le lit du mur.
I have approached (who? You? No, the bed of course) the bed from the wall.

Your pronunciation is better than some people in my college French classes. You change a lot of you vowels into "ee" sounds though. "j'ai" "préparé" and "le" sound like "j'y" "priparé" and "li" here. French has a lot of "e" sounds so this is a tricky part.
It's normal to have a hard time with vocab at first. Your brain isn't good at remembering words with unfamiliar structure. I had this problem with Chinese, where for the first month every word just sounded like "chingchong" basically. You just need to get used to the sounds before your brain is able to make strong memories.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>175334024
There's probably an optimal strategy, but there's so much noise in the language learning community and so many methods, that there's no real way to know what's actually good and what generally wastes your time. Some people think, speak early, others are for comprehensible input, third group thinks grammar drills are king etc.

In general, whole process boils down to: learn the words and how to put them in the right order. Only thing most people seem to agree on is that you should use Anki for vocabulary.

In my opinion, best strategy is to pick an easy language as your first language to learn (out of the N that you plan), then try every method you can and see what works for you. Try to measure or evaluate your progress regularly, can you comprehend something you previously couldn't? Can you produce sentences more easily than before? Do you know more words? And so on. This will help you not stagnate and remove activities out of your daily routine that just aren't efficient or worthwhile (like fucking Duolingo).

After your first language, you will learn from your mistakes and you can optimize your approach on the second one, each language refining your own personal method that's a culmination of a bunch of various strategies applied in a particular way. Then you can make big bux shilling your method on YouTube by calling yourself a polyglot in order to finance your cosmopolitan lifestyle.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>175334095
Repeating stuff in order to practice pronunciation or to better remember it is fine, I think he was just warning against early output in terms of trying to talk to people and write i.e. constructing your own sentences. I don't think it's harmful per se, but in the beginning you know so little words and you don't have an intuitive sense for the grammar so it's both frustrating and doesn't do much for you. You will be producing incorrect sentences and you'll spend most of your time reading about grammar and sometimes you might even learn wrong if there is no one there to correct you.

In my opinion, you're better off putting those hours into reading a book or listening. When you start constructing your own messages after at least a couple months, it's going to flow much more easily, you reach for a word and its already there, and you won't have to think about 50 rules to figure out the word order and which declension to use, in the middle of expressing a complex thought. If your goal is fluency, you should be off-loading as much of your language processing to your subconscious, not consciously thinking about grammar. You can use grammar knowledge to check and monitor yourself but it won't help you produce language spontaneously.
